function x = irtp (p, n);% IRTP Inverse Real Trigonometric Polynomial %    X = IRTP (P) ->	reconstructs the time-domain signal X from%    its RTP coefficients P. For matrices, the IRTP operation is%    applied to each column. %%    X = IRTP (P,N) ->	in this case the length of the output will%    be N*length(P), where N must be a positive non-zero integer. %    For N=1, the output will be the same as IRTP(P). For n>1, the output%    will be an "upsampled by factor of N" interpolation of IRTP(P).% %    Example: %    x = sin(2*pi*[0:0.1:0.9]); %    p = rtp(x);%    x_orig = irtp(p);%    x_2 = irtp(p,2);%    x_3 = irtp(p,3);%    x_orig = [0             0.588             0.951 ...%    x_2    = [0    0.309    0.588    0.809    0.951 ...%    x_3    = [0 0.208 0.407 0.588 0.743 0.866 0.951 ...%%    Note: The first element of IRTP(P,N) always corresponds to the %    t=0 element of the time-domain signal. % %    The inverse function is RTP.%% 	 See also RTP, HR_SHIFT, HR_ALIGN, HR_INTERP.% Copyright (c) 2006-2009. Kevin C. McGill and others.% Part of EMGlab version 1.0.% This work is licensed under the Aladdin free public license.% For copying permissions see license.txt.% email: emglab@emglab.net	if nargin<2; n=1; end;	[c, lx, l2] = rtp_to_dft (p);	c(n*lx-l2+2:n*lx,:) = conj(c(l2:-1:2,:));	x = n*real(ifft(c)) * sqrt(lx/2);